+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01JSNHXjFHH3uhEDHMKqRfFA","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Interesting! The `OPEN` event fires, and the `message` event fires with the sync message, BUT then the test times out. The timeout is 15 seconds. Looking at the output:\n- OPEN fires\n- But \"TIMEOUT, readyState: 1\" also prints — that's the 3-second fallback from the `connected` promise.\n\nWait, both `OPEN` and `TIMEOUT` fire? That means `resolve(true)` was called from the `open` event first (OPEN prints first), but then `setTimeout` also fires and prints TIMEOUT. That's expected behavior — the timer doesn't clear.\n\nBut the test says it failed at 15 seconds, which means the test function itself is hanging. The `connected` should be `true`, so it enters the `if (connected)` block and waits for the message. But the OPEN event already fired... and the message should have been sent by the server. \n\nAH WAIT. I see the problem! The `ws.on('message', ...)` handler is being registered AFTER the `open` event handler. But the sync message is sent right when the connection is established. Since we await the `connected` promise first (which resolves when `open` fires), by the time we register the `message` handler, the sync message may have already been received and discarded!\n\nThis is a race condition. In the working debug test, I registered the `message` handler immediately after creating the WebSocket (before `open` fires). But in the test file, the pattern is:\n\n```\nws.on('open', ...)   // register open handler\nawait connected       // wait for open\nws.on('message', ...) // register message handler - TOO LATE!\n```\n\nThe sync message was sent right when the connection was established. By the time the test awaits `connected` and then registers the `message` handler, the message has already been emitted and lost.\n\nSame issue in the server.test.ts: `connectWs` waits for `open`, then `waitForMessage` registers the `message` handler. But the sync message fires immediately on connection, so by the time `waitForMessage` is called, the message is already gone.\n\nThe fix: register the `message` handler before the `open` event, or at least in parallel. Let me update the test helpers."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1683,"cache_read_input_tokens":118148,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1683},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7d597816-e270-41ad-890d-62bb5d31fca5","uuid":"979f3179-f21d-4e0c-ac94-255c7f9eb09f"}
